03954nam a22004935i 9780773588981DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20132013xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735889817 a10.1515/97807735889812doi  a(DE-B1597)656774  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPN56.L33bM55 2013eb 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a809/.9335542231 aMiller, Jeffrey, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Structures of Law and Literature :bDuty, Justice, and Evil in the Cultural Imagination /cJeffrey Miller. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (264 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tFirst Principles and Controversies: Is Law and Literature More Than a Distraction for Bored Law Professors? -- tTowards a Typology, Iconography, and Symbology of Law and Literature -- tIt’s a Dutiful Day in the Neighbourhood: Duty as the Fulcrum on the Scales of Justice and the Centre of Community -- tThe Evil That Persons Do: Unreasonableness and the Rejection or Abnegation of Duty -- tHumpty Dumpty in Wig and Gown: Legalese as Dialect, or, the Philology of Precedent -- tPutting It All Together: The Structures of Law and Literature – Law as Revolution, Justice as Nostalgia -- tGlossary of Some Terms Used in This Book -- tNotes -- tSelect Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDo law and literature really have anything to say to each other? Until now, that threshold question has vexed law and literature studies. This revolutionary work provides a bold new answer, showing how law and literature spring from the same cultural impulses. Drawing on the archetypal criticism of Northrop Frye, the book takes a unique, quasi-scientific approach to the subject, covering both law in literature and law as literature. The Structures of Law and Literature moves beyond the works usually studied in the field (Charles Dickens, Franz Kafka, Herman Melville, Harper Lee) to consider traditional ballads, the biblical narratives of Moses and Job, literature from South Africa and France, as well as works in Yiddish and Hebrew, the poetry of W.B. Yeats, stories by John Updike, John Mortimer, and John Sayles, Scottish nationalist writing by James Kelman, the golem legend from the Talmud to modern novels, and more. It also investigates legalese as a dialect in a universe of its own making, provides a concise summary of the entire method proposed, and concludes with essays on selected works that render the method's application particularly graphic. Original and systematically argued, The Structures of Law and Literature is a provocative work that adds new dimensions to the cultural interplay of law and the humanities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aLaw and literature. 0aLaw in literature. 0aLegal literaturexHistory. 0aSociological jurisprudence. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077358898140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773588981423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773588981/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles